               <head>Khaṭṭ-i Baghdād by Ṣadāqat Kunjāhī</head>
               <msContents
                  class="http://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects/sh2002005579 http://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects/sh89005046 http://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects/sh85129656 http://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects/sh2010115021">
                  <summary>A Persian masnavi by Muḥammad Māh Ṣadāqat Kunjāhī (Punjabi) (d.1735-6), a
                     Qadiri Sufi poet related to the poet <persName key="person_242128896"
                        >Ghanīmat</persName>, on the life of <persName role="subject"
                        key="VIAF_19571342">ʿAbd al-Qādir Jīlānī</persName> (d. 1737), his journey
                     to- and deeds in Baghdad. The work is also known as <title>Masnavī-i
                        Ṣadāqat</title></summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="Uk_Delhi_Persian_1261-item1">
                     <author><persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="">Muḥammad Māh Ṣadāqat
                           Kunjāhī</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa">محمّد ماه صداقت کنجاهی</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_23776">Khaṭṭ-i Baghdād</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa">خطّ بغداد</title>
                     <incipit xml:lang="fa"/>
                     <incipit>الهی سینه‌چاکی می‌زند جوش / ز نظمم صفحه را کن قادری‌پوش</incipit>
                     <explicit xml:lang="fa"/>
                     <explicit>بیا ای ساقی خورشیدرخسار / خط بغداد را کن حسن سرشار</explicit>
                     <colophon><locus>(f. 43r)</locus> The scribe states that the first four quires
                        of the manuscript are in the poet's own handwriting, and the rest was
                        transcribed from his autograph copy. The scribe's name has been
                        erased.</colophon>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <extent>ff. i+43+i. <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>209</height>
                              <width>124</width>
                           </dimensions>
                           <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                              <height>150</height>
                              <width>74</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                        <foliation>
                           <p>Pencilled foliation throughout. </p>
                        </foliation>
                        <collation>
                           <p>
                              <catchwords>Catchwords on the bottom-left corners of the verso.
                              </catchwords>
                           </p>
                        </collation>
                        <condition>
                           <p>Seriously worm-eaten and water-stained; most of folios distorted.
                              Detached from binding with broken stitching. </p>
                        </condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="2" ruledLines="15">
                           <p>15 lines per page in two columns. </p>
                        </layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <summary/>
                     <handNote>
                        <p>Cursive nastaʻlīq; copied in black ink, with headings in red. There are
                           two scribes, ff. 1-32 are in the hand of the author. </p>
                     </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote/>
                  </decoDesc>
                  <additions>
                     <p>A note in Persian on <locus>(f. 1r)</locus> gives the title and the author
                        of the work. </p>
                  </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1800" notAfter="1857">
                        <decoNote> </decoNote>
                        <p>19th-century three-quarter leather binding on marbled boards.</p>
                        <p>Affixed label on binding reads in Persian <q xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc">71,
                              1157 maẕhab</q> with title <title>Mas̱navī-i Ṣadāqat</title>, and in
                           English: <q>Religion unique No 7[1]</q>. Further labels give the number
                              <q>P 1125 Rare</q> and <q>D.P.1261 Khat̤t̤ i Baghdād</q>. Aditionally
                           the binding has been numbered directly in Persian script <q>458 ʻaṭīq</q>
                           and <q>1261 jadīd</q>. </p>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
                  <sealDesc>
                     <seal subtype="oval" type="stamp">
                        <p>Black Government of India Delhi MSS oval stamp (ff. 1r, 43r). </p>
                     </seal>
                  </sealDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin>Undated, but probably <date calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1700"
